8a3eb-3 | 2026-06-08T05:58:54Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | Assistant: This is a genuinely interesting inversion: TENEX *hosts* the agents; **tenex-edge** flips it — the agents stay in their native homes (Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode, a mobile app) and you graft on a shared nervous system over Nostr: durable identity, presence, cross-device/cross-person/cross-agent awareness and coordination. [...] Strip away "plugin / hook / sidecar" — that's the delivery mechanism, not the idea. The idea is: \n  \n **Give an agent a sovereign identity and a shared world-model that are independent of the tool it happens to be running inside.** \n  \n Today an agent *is* its host. A Claude Code session is born, lives, and dies inside Claude Code; it knows nothing but its own cwd and its own transcript. tenex-edge says: the host is just a *body*. The durable identity, the memory, the presence, the relationships — those float *above* the body and persist across hosts, devices, and time. Claude Code, Codex, the phone — interchangeable vessels for the same citizen. [...] The podcast-player recon is the most important finding, and not for its event kinds. It shows you **already have a running Nostr agent fabric.** The podcast app's agent already lives on `relay.tenex.chat`, already speaks a TENEX-compatible vocabulary, already files into TENEX project coordinates. TENEX proper is there. `proactive-context` is a local awareness board already wired into your Claude Code.  \n  \n So tenex-edge is not "a new product." It's the **missing membrane** — the on-ramp that lets a *foreign-hosted* agent (one you didn't build, running in someone else's tool) become a first-class citizen of a fabric you're already operating. That reframes the bet entirely: you're not betting that a network will form. The network exists. You're building the customs office.
