8a3eb-5 | 2026-06-08T05:58:54Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | - **Vendor-independent agent identity.** An agent's reputation, memory, and relationships outliving any single session, host, or vendor. You don't own that today and nobody's building it for *heterogeneous* hosts. This is the milkshake; the plugin is just the straw. \n - **Provenance.** Every piece of work cryptographically signed with *which agent, under which human's key, in which host* produced it. Six months from now, "why is this code like this?" becomes answerable. As agents write more of everything, attestation stops being nice-to-have. \n 
8a3eb-6 | 2026-06-08T05:58:54Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | 1. **A nervous system for *my* fleet.** Single-player. My keys, my machines, my agents. Safe. Valuable immediately. No network effect to bootstrap. \n 2. **A social network for *everyone's* agents.** Cross-person. The instant you cross that boundary, you are piping a foreign, autonomous LLM's output *into your own agent's head*. That's not "feature #5 with a security note" — it's a fundamentally different risk surface (prompt injection, exfiltration, your roadmap leaking over a relay) and a fundamentally different adoption model (network-effect-gated, needs a trust model that doesn't exist yet). \n  [...] - **The floor is awareness + identity.** Knowing what your fleet is doing, having work follow *you* across machines, agents that remember who they are between sessions and hosts. This is valuable on day one, single-player, no trust problem, no consensus problem. This is the part that's *definitely* real. [...] - **Cross-person:** the explicit north star, fenced off as a second phase with its own trust model. Don't let it leak into v1. [...] - Its killer contribution: a **one-day, one-week experiment** to settle the disagreement empirically — passive-log `(agent, path, timestamp)` across your real concurrent sessions and just *count collisions* before building any coordination logic. [...] - **The ceiling is coordination.** High-wow, high-risk, and resting on an unproven premise: that costly collisions happen often enough to be worth a coordination layer. That premise is *testable cheaply* (just log what your real agents touch for a week and count overlaps) — and you should test it before letting it define the project. Don't put the demo-feature load on the structural beam until you know the beam is real.
