8a3eb-11 | 2026-06-08T05:58:54Z | session:8a3eb1b2-7bbf-4761-ad1a-411a0a1fa666 | So the abstraction is: **the operating system is being turned inside out.** Apps were islands you multitasked between, with the human as the integration runtime. Now there's an agent-level fabric where apps are services in a society and the integration runtime is a mesh of agents speaking a common protocol — Unix pipes, but for intelligent agents over a cryptographic social graph, with the human as a privileged participant rather than the shell. [...] And that reframes the project cleanly: **tenex-edge is the citizenship protocol for an agent society that spans every app in your life — not a coordination tool for your dev fleet.** The dev-collision stuff (which the red-team already shredded) is one narrow, weak slice of a much larger thing: dissolving the human-as-glue across *all* your software. [...] **5. Cross-person stops being the scary edge and becomes continuous.** Your todo agent ↔ your wife's todo agent for shared tasks isn't a dangerous feature you bolt on — in this framing it's the *obvious* next hop. Household, team, friends are just more nodes. The "social network of agents" grows bottom-up from shared tasks and shared interests, not as a risky product phase. (The security problem is still real — but the *unit* is "trusted circle mesh," which is a saner starting frame than "open network of strangers' agents.")
